    <div class="page-intro">
      <h1>JAMB Literature in English Syllabus</h1>
      <p class="muted">Complete topic breakdown for JAMB Literature. Includes selected texts and analysis guides.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="page-intro-actions" style="display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:center;margin-top:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <a href="#" class="btn-outline">Download PDF</a>
      <a href="../JambSyllabus.htm" class="btn-outline">← Back to All Subjects</a>
    </div>

    <div class="syllabus-table-wrap" style="overflow:auto;margin-top:18px;">
      <table class="syllabus-table" style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;min-width:920px;">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background:#f3fff3;">
            <th style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #e6e6e6;text-align:left;">Section</th>
            <th style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #e6e6e6;text-align:left;">Topics / Focus</th>
            <th style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #e6e6e6;text-align:left;">Details / Objectives</th>
            <th style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #e6e6e6;text-align:left;">Recommended Texts</th>
            <th style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #e6e6e6;text-align:left;">OAE Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">1<br><strong>Drama</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Types: Tragedy, Comedy, Tragicomedy, Melodrama, Farce, Opera<br>Techniques: Characterization, Dialogue, Soliloquy, Stagecraft</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Interpret themes, plot, setting and socio-political context; analyze dramatic techniques and compare playwright styles.</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Soyinka (plays), Osborne (Look Back in Anger), Critical texts (Abrams)</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:middle;"><a href="notes/literature/drama.htm">Check OAE notes</a></td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">2<br><strong>Prose</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Types: Novel, Novella, Short story, Biography, Memoir, Faction<br>Techniques: POV, Characterization, Narrative structure</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Differentiate prose types, analyze narrative techniques and relate texts to real-life issues.</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Emecheta, Brontë (Wuthering Heights), Selected African prose collections</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:middle;"><a href="notes/literature/prose.htm">Check OAE notes</a></td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">3<br><strong>Poetry</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Forms: Sonnet, Ode, Lyric, Elegy, Ballad, Epic, Blank verse<br>Devices: Imagery, Sound, Diction, Persona</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Identify poetic forms, analyze devices, interpret themes and socio-political relevance.</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Senghor, Osundare, Donne, Angelou, Eliot</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:middle;"><a href="notes/literature/poetry.htm">Check OAE notes</a></td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">4<br><strong>General Literary Principles</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Foreshadowing, Symbolism, Satire, Stream of Consciousness, Monologue, Dialogue</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Identify and apply literary terms; analyze their function in texts.</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Abrams (A Glossary of Literary Terms), Nwoga (West African Verse)</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:middle;"><a href="notes/literature/general-principles.htm">Check OAE notes</a></td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">5<br><strong>Literary Appreciation</strong></td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Unseen extracts from Drama, Prose and Poetry</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Identify devices, interpret meanings and relate to real-life applications.</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:top;">Murphy (Understanding Unseen), Anthologies listed below</td>
            <td style="padding:12px;border:1px solid #eee;vertical-align:middle;"><a href="notes/literature/literary-appreciation.htm">Check OAE notes</a></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- Prescribed & Recommended texts -->
    <div style="margin-top:20px;">
      <h2>Selected Prescribed Texts</h2>
      <p><strong>Drama:</strong> Wole Soyinka — Lion and the Jewel; John Osborne — Look Back in Anger</p>
      <p><strong>Prose:</strong> Buchi Emecheta — Second Class Citizen; Alex Agyei Agyiri — Unexpected Joy at Dawn; Emily Brontë — Wuthering Heights</p>
      <p><strong>Poetry:</strong> See recommended anthology list below (Senghor, Osundare, Maya Angelou, Donne, Eliot etc.)</p>

      <h2 style="margin-top:18px;">Recommended Texts</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Gbemisola A. — Naked Soles</li>
        <li>Hayward J. (ed.) — The Penguin Book of English Verse</li>
        <li>Johnson R. et al. (eds.) — New Poetry from Africa</li>
        <li>Kermode F. et al. — Oxford Anthology of English Literature Vol. II</li>
        <li>Nwoga D. (ed.) — West African Verse</li>
        <li>Parker E. W. (ed.) — A Pageant of Longer Poems</li>
        <li>Senanu K. E. & Vincent T. (eds.) — A Selection of African Poetry</li>
        <li>Soyinka W. (ed.) — Poems of Black Africa</li>
        <li>Abrams M. H. — A Glossary of Literary Terms</li>
        <li>Murphy M. J. — Understanding Unseen: An Introduction to English Poetry and Novel</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </main>

